[{"id":41911,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["C, D, E Only","A, D, E Only","B, C, D Only","A, B, C Only"],"answer":0,"solution":"Surface tension arises due to extra energy of the molecules at the molecules at the surface as compared at the interior of a liquid. The coefficient of viscosity for a liquid decreases with rise in temperature where as it increases for gases with increase in temperature. The flow is turbulent for a Reynold's number greater than 2000. Stream lines never intersect in a steady flow.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41923,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$\\left(\\frac{\\sigma-2}{\\sigma+2}\\right)^{1 / 3}$","$\\left(\\frac{\\sigma}{\\sigma-1}\\right)^{1 / 3}$","$\\left(\\frac{\\sigma-1}{\\sigma}\\right)^{1 / 3}$","$\\left(\\frac{\\sigma+1}{\\sigma-1}\\right)^{1 / 3}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"weight $(w)=\\frac{4}{3} \\pi\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{D}^3-\\mathrm{d}^3}{8}\\right) \\sigma \\mathrm{g}$\nBuoyant force $\\left(\\mathrm{F}_{\\mathrm{b}}\\right)=1 \\times \\frac{4}{3} \\pi\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{D}^3}{8}\\right) \\cdot \\mathrm{g}$\nFor Just Float $\\Rightarrow \\mathrm{w}=\\mathrm{F}_{\\mathrm{b}}$\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\Rightarrow\\left(D^3-d^3\\right) \\sigma=D^3 \\\\ & \\Rightarrow 1-\\frac{d^3}{D^3}=\\frac{1}{\\sigma} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow 1-\\frac{1}{\\sigma}=\\left(\\frac{d}{D}\\right)^3 \\\\ & \\Rightarrow\\left(\\frac{\\sigma}{\\sigma-1}\\right)^{\\frac{1}{3}}=\\left(\\frac{D}{d}\\right)\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42001,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Using Pascals law,&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7bf4045f-a1fa-4dd2-9433-e0caa7afa0d4-image.png\" style=\"width: 280px; height: 136px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>g</mi></mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math> mass can lift <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math> in second case then</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>16</mn><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mn>16</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"}\" open=\"{\"><mrow><mi>Since</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>From equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math> we get</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mrow><mn>16</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>M</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>25600</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kg</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":42066,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$8 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$10 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$4 \\mathrm{~cm}$","$20 \\mathrm{~cm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Water will rise to the full length of capillary tube","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":42042,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$0.1 \\mathrm{~m}$","$0.15 \\mathrm{~m}$","$0.20 \\mathrm{~m}$","$0.25 \\mathrm{~m}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Given: Radius of air bubble,\n$$\nr=0.1 \\mathrm{~cm}=10^{-3} \\mathrm{~m}\n$$\nSurface tension of liquid,\n$$\nS=0.06 \\mathrm{~N} / \\mathrm{m}=6 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~N} / \\mathrm{m}\n$$\nDensity of liquid, $\\rho=10^3 \\mathrm{~kg} / \\mathrm{m}^3$\nExcess pressure inside the bubble,\n$$\n\\rho_{\\text {exe }}=1100 \\mathrm{Nm}^{-2}\n$$\nDepth of bubble below the liquid surface, $h=$ ?\nAs we know,\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n&\\rho_{\\text {Excess }}=h \\rho g+\\frac{2 s}{r} \\\\\n&\\Rightarrow \\quad 1100=h \\times 10^3 \\times 9.8+\\frac{2 \\times 6 \\times 10^{-2}}{10^{-3}} \\\\\n&\\Rightarrow \\quad 1100=9800 h+120 \\\\\n&\\Rightarrow \\quad 9800 h=1100-120 \\\\\n&\\Rightarrow \\quad h=\\frac{980}{9800}=0.1 \\mathrm{~m}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":42050,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$60 \\mathrm{Nm}^{-2}$","$180 \\mathrm{Nm}^{-2}$","$7500 \\mathrm{Nm}^{-2}$","$12500 \\mathrm{Nm}^{-2}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Pressure difference\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{P}_2-\\mathrm{P}_1=\\frac{1}{2} \\rho\\left(\\mathrm{v}_2^2-\\mathrm{v}_1^2\\right) \\\\\n& =\\frac{1}{2} \\times 1.2\\left((150)^2-(100)^2\\right) \\\\\n& =\\frac{1}{2} \\times 1.2(22500-10000) \\\\\n& =7500 \\mathrm{Nm}^{-2}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":42030,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$\\theta=\\tan ^{-1}\\left[\\frac{\\pi}{2}\\left(\\frac{\\rho_1-\\rho_2}{\\rho_1+\\rho_2}\\right)\\right]$","$\\theta=\\tan ^{-1} \\frac{\\pi}{2}\\left(\\frac{\\rho_1+\\rho_2}{\\rho_1-\\rho_2}\\right)$","$\\theta=\\tan ^{-1} \\pi\\left(\\frac{\\rho_1}{\\rho_2}\\right)$","$\\theta=\\tan ^{-1} \\frac{\\pi}{2}\\left(\\frac{\\rho_2}{\\rho_1}\\right)$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Pressure at interface A must be same from both the sides to be in equilibrium.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/FUBMoJUuU4YUB9j3N9zeuX5xh2VY4kUMOwIAhhGpuTQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n$\\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\quad &(\\mathrm{R} \\cos \\theta+\\mathrm{R} \\sin \\theta) \\rho_2 \\mathrm{~g} \\\\ &=(\\mathrm{R} \\cos \\theta-\\mathrm{R} \\sin \\theta) \\rho_1 \\mathrm{~g} \\end{aligned}$\n$\\Rightarrow \\quad \\frac{\\rho_1}{\\rho_2}=\\frac{\\cos \\theta+\\sin \\theta}{\\cos \\theta-\\sin \\theta}=\\frac{1+\\tan \\theta}{1-\\tan \\theta}$\n$\\Rightarrow \\rho_1-\\rho_1 \\tan \\theta=\\rho_2+\\rho_2 \\tan \\theta$\n$\\Rightarrow \\quad\\left(\\rho_1+\\rho_2\\right) \\tan \\theta=\\rho_1-\\rho_2$\n$\\therefore \\quad \\theta=\\tan ^{-1}\\left(\\frac{\\rho_1-\\rho_2}{\\rho_1+\\rho_2}\\right)$, soclosest answer is (a)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":41932,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true and Statement II is false"],"answer":2,"solution":"Capillary rise\n$\\mathrm{h}=\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~T} \\cos \\theta}{\\rho \\mathrm{gr}} \\text {; }$\nIf $\\theta=0^{\\circ}$ then rise is non-zero\n$\\therefore$ Statement-1 is incorrect.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41918,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$4 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$","$2 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$","$6 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$","$8 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/wBp8rl_wqJ4KY9EwqTmXYN8aKA8zGhGnXEP2bkbY8js.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{A}_1 \\mathrm{~V}_1=\\mathrm{A}_2 \\mathrm{~V}_2 \\Rightarrow 2 \\pi(2 \\mathrm{R})^2=\\mathrm{V}_2 \\pi \\mathrm{R}^2 \\\\ & \\therefore \\mathrm{~V}_2=8 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41963,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>20</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>10</mn></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The height <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> through which a liquid will rise in a capillary tube of radius <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math> is given by,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>T</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#952;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mi>T</mi><mi>&#961;</mi></mfrac><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#961;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>As we can see in both cases, value of height will remain same. Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>h</mi><mo>'</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41985,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/641eb6c2-2e2f-47a4-a751-66336d9d671d-image.png\" style=\"width: 290px; height: 113px;\" /></p><p>From equation of continuity,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></p><p>From Bernoulli&#39;s theorem,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>&#961;</mi><msup><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>g</mi><msub><mi>h</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>&#961;</mi><msup><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>g</mi><msub><mi>h</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>&#961;</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>h</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>h</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><msup><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>4100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>800</mn><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>10</mn><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mn>3</mn><msup><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>4100</mn><mn>800</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>121</mn><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>363</mn></msqrt><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace></math></p><p>Therefore,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>363</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41937,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn></math> times","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math> times","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mi>th</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mi>th</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Lets say radius of small droplets is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math> and that of big drop is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math>. Total volume of the drops will remains unchanged. Therefore, </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1000</mn><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>r</mi></math></p><p>Now, initial surface energy is, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1000</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>S</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> and the final surface energy is, </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>S</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>S</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>Clearly, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42056,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$5 \\mathrm{~m} \\mathrm{~s}^{-1}$","$10 \\mathrm{~m} \\mathrm{~s}^{-1}$","$25 \\mathrm{~m} \\mathrm{~s}^{-1}$","$50 \\sqrt{10} \\mathrm{~m} \\mathrm{~s}^{-1}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"According to Bernoulli's theorem\n$$\nP_1+\\frac{1}{2} \\rho v_1^2=P_2+\\frac{1}{2} \\rho v_2^2 \\ldots(\\mathrm{i})\n$$\nFrom question,\n$$\nP_1-P_2=3 \\times 10^5, \\frac{A_1}{A_2}=5\n$$\nAccording to equation of continuity\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& A_1 v_1=A_2 v_2 \\\\\n& \\text { or, } \\frac{A_1}{A_2}=\\frac{v_2}{v_1}=5 \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\quad v_2=5 v_1\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nFrom equation (i)\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& P_1-P_2=\\frac{1}{2} \\rho\\left(v_2^2-v_1^2\\right) \\\\\n& \\text { or } 3 \\times 10^5=\\frac{1}{2} \\times 1000\\left(5 v_1^2-v_1^2\\right. \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\quad 600=6 v_1 \\times 4 v_1 \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\quad v_1^2=25 \\\\\n& \\therefore \\quad v_1=5 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (12 May Online)","image":null},{"id":41891,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["3.0","1.0","2.0","1.5"],"answer":2,"solution":"Using Stokes' Law for terminal velocity:<br>$v_t = \\frac{2r^2g(\\rho_s - \\rho_f)}{9\\eta}$. <br>Given: r = 0.1 cm, g = 1000 cm/s², $\\rho_s = 10.5$ g/cm³, $\\rho_f = 1.5$ g/cm³, η = 10 Poise = 10 g/(cm⋅s). <br>Substituting:<br>$v_t = \\frac{2 \\times (0.1)^2 \\times 1000 \\times (10.5 - 1.5)}{9 \\times 10}$ <br>$= \\frac{2 \\times 0.01 \\times 1000 \\times 9}{90}$ <br>$= \\frac{180}{90} = 2.0$ cm/s.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41941,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>T</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Let radius of the newly formed drops be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math>.</p><p>As total volume will remain constant, therefore</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>×</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>r</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>9</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Now, work done <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>T</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>Δ</mi><mi>A</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>T</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>27</mn><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mi>T</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mi>T</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>27</mn><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi><mfrac><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>9</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mi>T</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mi>T</mi><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>12</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>π</mi><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>T</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41892,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["4.5","2.0","4.2","3.0"],"answer":0,"solution":"An air bubble rises through water with initial volume 2.9 cm³ at the bottom. Calculating pressures at both locations: <br>At bottom (5 m depth): $P_1 = P_{atm} + \\rho gh = 10^5 + 10^3(10)(5) = 1.5 \\times 10^5$ Pa <br>At surface: $P_2 = 10^5$ Pa <br>Initial temperature: $T_1 = 17°C = 290$ K, Final temperature: $T_2 = 27°C = 300$ K <br>Using ideal gas law: $\\frac{P_1V_1}{T_1} = \\frac{P_2V_2}{T_2}$ <br>$V_2 = V_1 \\times \\frac{P_1}{P_2} \\times \\frac{T_2}{T_1} = 2.9 \\times \\frac{1.5 \\times 10^5}{10^5} \\times \\frac{300}{290}$ <br>$= 2.9 \\times 1.5 \\times \\frac{30}{29} = 2.9 \\times 1.5 \\times 1.034 \\approx 4.5$ cm³","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":42055,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Mechanical Properties of Fluids","question":"","options":["$\\left[\\frac{T}{\\rho}\\left(\\frac{1}{r}-\\frac{1}{R}\\right)\\right]^{1 / 2}$","$\\left[\\frac{6 T}{\\rho}\\left(\\frac{1}{r}-\\frac{1}{R}\\right)\\right]^{1 / 2}$","$\\left[\\frac{3 T}{\\rho}\\left(\\frac{1}{r}-\\frac{1}{R}\\right)\\right]^{1 / 2}$","$\\left[\\frac{2 T}{\\rho}\\left(\\frac{1}{r}-\\frac{1}{R}\\right)\\right]^{1 / 2}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"When small droplets coelesce to form a bigger drop, energy released in this process is given by,\n$$\n4 \\pi R^3 T\\left[\\frac{1}{r}-\\frac{1}{R}\\right]\n$$\nWhere, $R=$ radius of big drop\n$r=$ radius of small drop\n$T=$ surface tension\nAccording to question\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\frac{1}{2} m v^2=4 \\pi R^3 T\\left[\\frac{1}{r}-\\frac{1}{R}\\right] \\\\\n\\Rightarrow & \\frac{1}{2}\\left[\\frac{4}{3} \\pi R^3 \\rho\\right] v^2=4 \\pi R^3 T\\left[\\frac{1}{r}-\\frac{1}{R}\\right] \\\\\n\\Rightarrow V^2 & =\\frac{6 T}{\\rho}\\left[\\frac{1}{r}-\\frac{1}{R}\\right] \\Rightarrow V=\\left[\\frac{6 T}{\\rho}\\left(\\frac{1}{r}-\\frac{1}{R}\\right)\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null}]